Laboratory exercises in the course Introduction to Programming are performed by students in a FER lab, following precisely prescribed terms. There are four exercises in each of the two cycles (total 8 exercises), with each exercise taking approximately 110 minutes to complete. The laboratory exercise consists of two parts: solving tasks using multiple choice questions and creating one or more programs. Students work independently on the faculty computer under the supervision of teachers on duty. They use the same tools as they do on their own computers, such as Notepad/Notepad++ editors, gcc compiler via command line, and VSCode development environment. The exact schedule, topics, and number of program tasks per exercise will be published on Teams at least a week before the exercises. Students submit solutions to their tasks during laboratory exercises via the Edgar system.
